{
  "video_id": "Ytr28t5VzAs",
  "title": "Where do new words come from? - Marcel Danesi",
  "es": 0,
  "json": [
    {
      "index": 1,
      "start_time": 7340.0,
      "end_time": 12870.0,
      "text": "Every year, about 1,000 new words are added to the Oxford English Dictionary."
    },
    {
      "index": 2,
      "start_time": 12871.0,
      "end_time": 14310.0,
      "text": "Where do they come from,"
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "start_time": 14310.0,
      "end_time": 17627.0,
      "text": "and how do they make it  into our everyday lives?"
    },
    {
      "index": 4,
      "start_time": 17627.0,
      "end_time": 22482.0,
      "text": "With over 170,000 words currently in use in the English language,"
    },
    {
      "index": 5,
      "start_time": 22482.0,
      "end_time": 25970.0,
      "text": "it might seem we already have plenty."
    },
    {
      "index": 6,
      "start_time": 25970.0,
      "end_time": 27779.0,
      "text": "Yet, as our world changes,"
    },
    {
      "index": 7,
      "start_time": 27779.0,
      "end_time": 30111.0,
      "text": "new ideas and inventions spring forth,"
    },
    {
      "index": 8,
      "start_time": 30111.0,
      "end_time": 31781.0,
      "text": "and science progresses,"
    },
    {
      "index": 9,
      "start_time": 31781.0,
      "end_time": 36330.0,
      "text": "our existing words leave gaps in what we want to express"
    },
    {
      "index": 10,
      "start_time": 36331.0,
      "end_time": 39710.0,
      "text": "and we fill those gaps  in several ingenious,"
    },
    {
      "index": 11,
      "start_time": 39710.0,
      "end_time": 40560.0,
      "text": "practical,"
    },
    {
      "index": 12,
      "start_time": 40570.0,
      "end_time": 43851.0,
      "text": "and occasionally peculiar ways."
    },
    {
      "index": 13,
      "start_time": 43851.0,
      "end_time": 47501.0,
      "text": "One way is to absorb a word from another language."
    },
    {
      "index": 14,
      "start_time": 47502.0,
      "end_time": 50721.0,
      "text": "English has borrowed so many words over its history"
    },
    {
      "index": 15,
      "start_time": 50721.0,
      "end_time": 56509.0,
      "text": "that nearly half of its vocabulary comes directly from other languages."
    },
    {
      "index": 16,
      "start_time": 56509.0,
      "end_time": 59728.0,
      "text": "Sometimes, this is simply because the thing the word describes"
    },
    {
      "index": 17,
      "start_time": 59728.0,
      "end_time": 62238.0,
      "text": "was borrowed itself."
    },
    {
      "index": 18,
      "start_time": 62241.0,
      "end_time": 65651.0,
      "text": "Rome and France brought legal and religious concepts,"
    },
    {
      "index": 19,
      "start_time": 65651.0,
      "end_time": 68890.0,
      "text": "like altar and jury, to Medieval England,"
    },
    {
      "index": 20,
      "start_time": 68891.0,
      "end_time": 71582.0,
      "text": "while trade brought crops and cuisine,"
    },
    {
      "index": 21,
      "start_time": 71582.0,
      "end_time": 72881.0,
      "text": "like Arabic coffee,"
    },
    {
      "index": 22,
      "start_time": 72882.0,
      "end_time": 74413.0,
      "text": "Italian spaghetti,"
    },
    {
      "index": 23,
      "start_time": 74413.0,
      "end_time": 76933.0,
      "text": "and Indian curry."
    },
    {
      "index": 24,
      "start_time": 76933.0,
      "end_time": 79970.0,
      "text": "But sometimes, another language  has just the right word"
    },
    {
      "index": 25,
      "start_time": 79970.0,
      "end_time": 82753.0,
      "text": "for a complex idea or emotion,"
    },
    {
      "index": 26,
      "start_time": 82753.0,
      "end_time": 83963.0,
      "text": "like naïveté"
    },
    {
      "index": 27,
      "start_time": 83963.0,
      "end_time": 85103.0,
      "text": "machismo,"
    },
    {
      "index": 28,
      "start_time": 85103.0,
      "end_time": 87178.0,
      "text": "or schadenfreude."
    },
    {
      "index": 29,
      "start_time": 87179.0,
      "end_time": 91433.0,
      "text": "Scientists also use classical languages to name new concepts."
    },
    {
      "index": 30,
      "start_time": 91433.0,
      "end_time": 96454.0,
      "text": "Clone, for example, was derived from the Ancient Greek word for twig"
    },
    {
      "index": 31,
      "start_time": 96454.0,
      "end_time": 101120.0,
      "text": "to describe creating a new plant from a piece of the old."
    },
    {
      "index": 32,
      "start_time": 101130.0,
      "end_time": 104704.0,
      "text": "And today, the process works both ways,"
    },
    {
      "index": 33,
      "start_time": 104704.0,
      "end_time": 109883.0,
      "text": "with English lending words like software to languages all over the world."
    },
    {
      "index": 34,
      "start_time": 109883.0,
      "end_time": 114240.0,
      "text": "Another popular way  to fill a vocabulary gap"
    },
    {
      "index": 35,
      "start_time": 114250.0,
      "end_time": 119334.0,
      "text": "is by combining existing words that each convey part of the new concept."
    },
    {
      "index": 36,
      "start_time": 119334.0,
      "end_time": 123365.0,
      "text": "This can be done by combining two whole words into a compound word,"
    },
    {
      "index": 37,
      "start_time": 123365.0,
      "end_time": 124545.0,
      "text": "like airport"
    },
    {
      "index": 38,
      "start_time": 124545.0,
      "end_time": 126226.0,
      "text": "or starfish,"
    },
    {
      "index": 39,
      "start_time": 126226.0,
      "end_time": 130853.0,
      "text": "or by clipping and blending parts of words together, like spork,"
    },
    {
      "index": 40,
      "start_time": 130854.00000000001,
      "end_time": 131644.0,
      "text": "brunch,"
    },
    {
      "index": 41,
      "start_time": 131644.0,
      "end_time": 133503.0,
      "text": "or internet."
    },
    {
      "index": 42,
      "start_time": 133503.0,
      "end_time": 135885.0,
      "text": "And unlike borrowings  from other languages,"
    },
    {
      "index": 43,
      "start_time": 135885.0,
      "end_time": 140594.0,
      "text": "these can often be understood the first time you hear them."
    },
    {
      "index": 44,
      "start_time": 140594.0,
      "end_time": 144116.0,
      "text": "And sometimes a new word isn't new at all."
    },
    {
      "index": 45,
      "start_time": 144116.0,
      "end_time": 148195.0,
      "text": "Obsolete words gain new life by adopting new meanings."
    },
    {
      "index": 46,
      "start_time": 148195.0,
      "end_time": 153454.0,
      "text": "Villain originally meant a peasant farmer, but in a twist of aristocratic snobbery"
    },
    {
      "index": 47,
      "start_time": 153455.0,
      "end_time": 158560.0,
      "text": "came to mean someone not bound by the knightly code of chivalry"
    },
    {
      "index": 48,
      "start_time": 158560.0,
      "end_time": 161326.0,
      "text": "and, therefore, a bad person."
    },
    {
      "index": 49,
      "start_time": 161326.0,
      "end_time": 164107.0,
      "text": "A geek went from  being a carnival performer"
    },
    {
      "index": 50,
      "start_time": 164107.0,
      "end_time": 165836.0,
      "text": "to any strange person"
    },
    {
      "index": 51,
      "start_time": 165836.0,
      "end_time": 169796.0,
      "text": "to a specific type of awkward genius."
    },
    {
      "index": 52,
      "start_time": 169796.0,
      "end_time": 174900.0,
      "text": "And other times, words come to mean their opposite through irony,"
    },
    {
      "index": 53,
      "start_time": 174900.0,
      "end_time": 175870.0,
      "text": "metaphor,"
    },
    {
      "index": 54,
      "start_time": 175870.0,
      "end_time": 177528.0,
      "text": "or misuse,"
    },
    {
      "index": 55,
      "start_time": 177528.0,
      "end_time": 184208.0,
      "text": "like when sick or wicked are used to describe something literally amazing."
    },
    {
      "index": 56,
      "start_time": 184208.0,
      "end_time": 186935.0,
      "text": "But if words can be formed in all these ways,"
    },
    {
      "index": 57,
      "start_time": 186935.0,
      "end_time": 190737.0,
      "text": "why do some become mainstream while others fall out of use"
    },
    {
      "index": 58,
      "start_time": 190737.0,
      "end_time": 194488.0,
      "text": "or never catch on in the first place?"
    },
    {
      "index": 59,
      "start_time": 194488.0,
      "end_time": 196238.0,
      "text": "Sometimes, the answer is simple,"
    },
    {
      "index": 60,
      "start_time": 196238.0,
      "end_time": 200367.0,
      "text": "as when scientists or companies  give an official name to a new discovery"
    },
    {
      "index": 61,
      "start_time": 200367.0,
      "end_time": 202447.0,
      "text": "or technology."
    },
    {
      "index": 62,
      "start_time": 202448.0,
      "end_time": 208490.0,
      "text": "And some countries have language academies to make the decisions."
    },
    {
      "index": 63,
      "start_time": 208490.0,
      "end_time": 211178.0,
      "text": "But for the most part, official sources like dictionaries"
    },
    {
      "index": 64,
      "start_time": 211178.0,
      "end_time": 214970.0,
      "text": "only document current usage."
    },
    {
      "index": 65,
      "start_time": 214970.0,
      "end_time": 218629.0,
      "text": "New words don't originate from above, but from ordinary people"
    },
    {
      "index": 66,
      "start_time": 218629.0,
      "end_time": 221688.0,
      "text": "spreading words that  hit the right combination"
    },
    {
      "index": 67,
      "start_time": 221688.0,
      "end_time": 224950.0,
      "text": "of useful and catchy."
    },
    {
      "index": 68,
      "start_time": 224950.0,
      "end_time": 226420.0,
      "text": "Take the word meme,"
    },
    {
      "index": 69,
      "start_time": 226420.0,
      "end_time": 230977.0,
      "text": "coined in the 1970s  by sociobiologist Richard Dawkins"
    },
    {
      "index": 70,
      "start_time": 230978.0,
      "end_time": 234539.0,
      "text": "from the Ancient Greek for imitation."
    },
    {
      "index": 71,
      "start_time": 234539.0,
      "end_time": 238869.0,
      "text": "He used it to describe how ideas and symbols propagate through a culture"
    },
    {
      "index": 72,
      "start_time": 238869.0,
      "end_time": 242181.0,
      "text": "like genes through a population."
    },
    {
      "index": 73,
      "start_time": 242181.0,
      "end_time": 243720.0,
      "text": "With the advent of the Internet,"
    },
    {
      "index": 74,
      "start_time": 243720.0,
      "end_time": 247919.0,
      "text": "the process became directly observable in how jokes and images"
    },
    {
      "index": 75,
      "start_time": 247919.0,
      "end_time": 251324.0,
      "text": "were popularized at lightning speed."
    },
    {
      "index": 76,
      "start_time": 251324.0,
      "end_time": 256103.0,
      "text": "And soon, the word came to refer to a certain kind of image."
    },
    {
      "index": 77,
      "start_time": 256103.0,
      "end_time": 259832.0,
      "text": "So meme not only describes how words become part of language,"
    },
    {
      "index": 78,
      "start_time": 259832.0,
      "end_time": 263382.0,
      "text": "the word is a meme itself."
    },
    {
      "index": 79,
      "start_time": 263382.0,
      "end_time": 267791.0,
      "text": "And there's a word for this phenomenon of words that describe themselves:"
    },
    {
      "index": 80,
      "start_time": 267791.0,
      "end_time": 269983.0,
      "text": "autological."
    },
    {
      "index": 81,
      "start_time": 269983.0,
      "end_time": 272555.0,
      "text": "Not all new words are created equal."
    },
    {
      "index": 82,
      "start_time": 272555.0,
      "end_time": 274557.0,
      "text": "Some stick around for millennia,"
    },
    {
      "index": 83,
      "start_time": 274557.0,
      "end_time": 276881.0,
      "text": "some adapt to changing times,"
    },
    {
      "index": 84,
      "start_time": 276881.0,
      "end_time": 279486.0,
      "text": "and others die off."
    },
    {
      "index": 85,
      "start_time": 279487.0,
      "end_time": 281252.0,
      "text": "Some relay information,"
    },
    {
      "index": 86,
      "start_time": 281252.0,
      "end_time": 282690.0,
      "text": "some interpret it,"
    },
    {
      "index": 87,
      "start_time": 282690.0,
      "end_time": 284762.0,
      "text": "but the way these words are created"
    },
    {
      "index": 88,
      "start_time": 284762.0,
      "end_time": 287769.0,
      "text": "and the journey they take to become part of our speech"
    },
    {
      "index": 89,
      "start_time": 287769.0,
      "end_time": 292630.0,
      "text": "tells us a lot about our world and how we communicate within it."
    }
  ]
}